9":"circa 1469","1364":"1364","about 1422":"circa 1422","1428":"1428","11 December 1400":"11 december 1400","about 1450":"circa 1450","King's Langley, Hertfordshire, England":"King's Langley, Hertfordshire, England","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Watford, Hertfordshire, England":"Watford, Hertfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1400–about 1469":"1400–about 1469","1400–1469":"1400–1469","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1428–1520":"1428–1520","1346–1446":"1346–1446","1364–1425":"1364–1425","1450":"1450","1425":"1425","1469":"1469","1446":"1446","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","about 1469":"about 1469","1364":"1364","about 1422":"about 1422","1428":"1428","11 December 1400":"11 December 1400","about 1450":"about 1450","King's Langley, Hertfordshire, England":"King's Langley, Hertfordshire, England","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Watford, Hertfordshire, England":"Watford, Hertfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Covert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Surrey, of Norman origin): habitational name from the Norman hamlet of Couvert in Calvados or from some other locality similarly named from Old French <i>(le) covert</i> ‘the secret corner, refuge, or thicket’. Sussex surname forms with the definite article and no preposition are not nicknames from Old French <i>covert</i> ‘secret(ive)’, as has been suggested, but are either references to ‘Le Covert’ as the place of origin or represent the common Norman practice of substituting <i>le</i> for <i>de</i> in surnames. This surname is now extinct in Britain.","Americanized form of an unidentified Dutch or German name, perhaps   Kofoed   or German   Gobert  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Coovert","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>Couvert</b> or its Dutch form <b>Coevert</b>, see   Covert  ."]},{"name":"Kofoed","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Anders, Nanna.","Danish: from <i>ko</i> ‘cow’ + <i>fod</i> ‘foot’, hence a nickname for someone with a club foot or other deformity of the foot. Compare   Kofford  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Abner","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, meaning ‘father of light’ in Hebrew. It was borne by a relative of King Saul, who was in command of Saul's army (1 Samuel 14:50; 26:5). It is not common as a given name in England, but has enjoyed a steady, modest popularity in America, where it dates back to the time of the earliest Puritan settlements."],"variants":[{"name":"Avner","meanings":["modern Hebrew form of   Abner ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Thomas John Abner Covert was born in 1400, in England, his father, John le Covert, was 54 and his mother, Joan le Carter, was 36. He married Lady Caroline Perrine about 1422, in Doncaster, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1469, in St Albans, Hertfordshire, England, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1400–about 1469":"1400–umbes 1469","1400–1469":"1400–1469","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1428–1520":"1428–1520","1346–1446":"1346–1446","1364–1425":"1364–1425","1450":"1450","1425":"1425","1469":"1469","1446":"1446","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","about 1469":"umbes 1469","1364":"1364","about 1422":"umbes 1422","1428":"1428","11 December 1400":"11. detsember 1400","about 1450":"umbes 1450","King's Langley, Hertfordshire, England":"King's Langley, Hertfordshire, England","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Watford, Hertfordshire, England":"Watford, Hertfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1400–about 1469":"1400–noin 1469","1400–1469":"1400–1469","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1428–1520":"1428–1520","1346–1446":"1346–1446","1364–1425":"1364–1425","1450":"1450","1425":"1425","1469":"1469","1446":"1446","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1520":"1520","about 1469":"noin 1469","1364":"1364","about 1422":"noin 1422","1428":"1428","11 December 1400":"11. joulukuuta 1400","about 1450":"noin 1450","King's Langley, Hertfordshire, England":"King's Langley, Hertfordshire, England","St Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Watford, Hertfordshire, England":"Watford, Hertfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1400–about 1469":"1400–environ 1469","1400–1469":"1400–1469","1400–